Baiera? sp. Pl. 2, fig. 16.

The fragment in pl. 2, fig. 16, may possibly represent the lower portion of a leaf of Baiera. It is wedge-like with spreading dichotomizing veins and is broken at both ends. It would appear as if it was bnanched, which would streng- then the probability of its being a Baiera, but this is not certain.

Pityophyllum? sp. Pl. 2, figs. 17, 18.

The small fragments shown in pl. 2, figs. 17 and 18, appear to represent coniferous leaves of the Pityophyllum- type. The largest specimen has a length of only 15 mm.; the breadth is 1——2 mm. In both specimens there is a dis- tinct midrib.
